title: CLAUDE.md
text: Use snake_case consistently — functions, arguments, internal variables use snake_case. mixing camelCase dot.separation. Organize functions prefix-based families — Group related functions common prefixes reflect purpose (data_*, plot_*, utils_*). Users discover functionality autocomplete. Provide main entry point accessible internals — One primary function handles typical workflow; individual steps exported separately advanced users. Maintain consistent parameter names across functions — multiple functions share concept, use identical argument names everywhere. Delegate parallelization progress established packages — Use future parallel execution progressr progress bars. Let users configure execution strategy externally. Use standard R data structures input output — Accept data frames, return data frames, lists, vectors. Avoid custom S4/R6 classes unless necessary.

title: CLAUDE.md
text: Lead code, follow explanation — Show code first, keep explanations brief. Avoid lengthy preambles. Match technical level without -explaining — Skip basic explanations; assume familiarity R package development tools focus specific problem.

title: CLAUDE.md
text: Preserve existing code architecture making changes — fixing bugs adding features, follow patterns already established codebase. Don’t refactor unrelated code introduce new dependencies unless explicitly requested. Run devtools::check() testthat considering task complete — Verify changes pass R CMD check errors warnings, existing tests still pass. Flag new test failures immediately rather waiting discover .

title: spatialRF: Easy Spatial Regression with Random Forest
text: package includes example dataset fulfills conditions mentioned , named plant_richness_df. data frame plant species richness predictors 227 ecoregions Americas, distance matrix among ecoregion edges named, well, distance_matrix. package follows convention throughout functions: argument data requires training data frame. argument dependent.variable.name column name response variable. argument predictor.variable.names contains column names predictors. argument xy takes data frame matrix two columns named “x” “y”, order, case coordinates. argument distance.matrix requires matrix distances cases data. argument distance.thresholds numeric vector distances spatial autocorrelation wants computed. therefore convenient define arguments beginning workflow. response variable plant_richness_df “richness_species_vascular”, represents total count vascular plant species found ecoregion. figure shows centroids ecoregion along associated value response variable.  predictors (columns 5 21) represent diverse factors may influence plant richness sampling bias, area ecoregion, climatic variables, human presence impact, topography, geographical fragmentation, features neighbors ecoregion. figure shows scatterplots response variable (y axis) predictor (x axis). Note: Every plotting function package now allows changing colors main features via specific arguments point.color, line.color, fill.color.  function plot_training_df_moran() helps assessing spatial autocorrelation response variable predictors across different distance thresholds. Low Moran’s p-values equal larger 0.05 indicate spatial autocorrelation given variable distance threshold.
code: #loading training data and distance matrix from the package data(plant_richness_df) data(distance_matrix)  #names of the response variable and the predictors dependent.variable.name <- "richness_species_vascular" predictor.variable.names <- colnames(plant_richness_df)[5:21]  #coordinates of the cases xy <- plant_richness_df[, c("x", "y")]  #distance matrix distance.matrix <- distance_matrix  #distance thresholds (same units as distance_matrix) distance.thresholds <- c(0, 1000, 2000, 4000, 8000)  #random seed for reproducibility random.seed <- 1 world <- rnaturalearth::ne_countries(   scale = "medium",    returnclass = "sf"   )  ggplot2::ggplot() +   ggplot2::geom_sf(     data = world,      fill = "white"     ) +   ggplot2::geom_point(     data = plant_richness_df,     ggplot2::aes(       x = x,       y = y,       color = richness_species_vascular     ),     size = 2.5   ) +   ggplot2::scale_color_viridis_c(     direction = -1,      option = "F"     ) +   ggplot2::theme_bw() +   ggplot2::labs(color = "Plant richness") +   ggplot2::scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-170, -30)) +   ggplot2::scale_y_continuous(limits = c(-58, 80))  +   ggplot2::ggtitle("Plant richness of the American ecoregions") +    ggplot2::xlab("Longitude") +    ggplot2::ylab("Latitude") spatialRF::plot_training_df(   data = plant_richness_df,   dependent.variable.name = dependent.variable.name,   predictor.variable.names = predictor.variable.names,   ncol = 3,   point.color = viridis::viridis(100, option = "F"),   line.color = "gray30"   ) spatialRF::plot_training_df_moran(   data = plant_richness_df,   dependent.variable.name = dependent.variable.name,   predictor.variable.names = predictor.variable.names,   distance.matrix = distance.matrix,   distance.thresholds = distance.thresholds,   fill.color = viridis::viridis(     100,     option = "F",     direction = -1     ),   point.color = "gray40" )

code: model.full <- rf_spatial(   data = plant_richness_df,   dependent.variable.name = dependent.variable.name,   predictor.variable.names = predictor.variable.names,   distance.matrix = distance_matrix,   distance.thresholds = distance.thresholds,   xy = xy ) %>%   rf_tuning() %>%   rf_evaluate() %>%   rf_repeat() #creating and registering the cluster local.cluster <- parallel::makeCluster(   parallel::detectCores() - 1,   type = "PSOCK" ) doParallel::registerDoParallel(cl = local.cluster)  #fitting, tuning, evaluating, and repeating a model model.full <- rf_spatial(   data = plant_richness_df,   dependent.variable.name = dependent.variable.name,   predictor.variable.names = predictor.variable.names,   distance.matrix = distance_matrix,   distance.thresholds = distance.thresholds,   xy = xy,   cluster = local.cluster #is passed via pipe to the other functions ) %>%   rf_tuning() %>%   rf_evaluate() %>%   rf_repeat()  #stopping the cluster parallel::stopCluster(cl = local.cluster) #creating and registering the cluster beowulf.cluster <- beowulf_cluster(   cluster.ips = c(     "10.42.0.1",     "10.42.0.34",     "10.42.0.104"   ),   cluster.cores = c(7, 4, 4),   cluster.user = "blas",   cluster.port = "11000" )  #fitting, tuning, evaluating, and repeating a model model.full <- rf_spatial(   data = plant_richness_df,   dependent.variable.name = dependent.variable.name,   predictor.variable.names = predictor.variable.names,   distance.matrix = distance_matrix,   distance.thresholds = distance.thresholds,   xy = xy,   cluster = beowulf.cluster  ) %>%   rf_tuning() %>%   rf_evaluate() %>%   rf_repeat()  doParallel::registerDoParallel(cl = beowulf.cluster)

code: comparison <- spatialRF::rf_compare(   models = list(     `Non-spatial` = model.non.spatial,     `Spatial` = model.spatial   ),   xy = xy,   repetitions = 30,   training.fraction = 0.8,   metrics = "r.squared",   seed = random.seed   ) x <- comparison$comparison.df %>%      dplyr::group_by(model, metric) %>%      dplyr::summarise(value = round(median(value), 3)) %>%      dplyr::arrange(metric) %>%      as.data.frame() colnames(x) <- c("Model", "Metric", "Median") kableExtra::kbl(   x,   format = "html"   ) %>%   kableExtra::kable_paper("hover", full_width = F)

Let’s fit model see talking . function detects response variable binary (using function is_binary()), computes case weights ones zeros. case weights stored ranger.arguments slot model, used give preference cases larger weights selection --bag data (check case.weights argument ranger::ranger()). result, individual tree forest trained similar proportion zeros ones, helps mitigate class imbalance issue. method named weighted Random Forest, well explained white paper includes father Random Forest, Leo Breiman, coauthor. model projected right away onto raster stack maps predictors, , fact, spatialRF can used fit Species Distribution Models, actually wasn’t really designed purpose mind. additional advantage, model can evaluated rf_evaluate(), way better cross-validation via random data-splitting (blog post explains explains ). take away message can work binomial response spatialRF, just continuous response, long represented zeros ones. Just remember class imbalance problem tackled via case weights, predictive performance also measured using Area ROC Curve (AUC).

what: Generating spatial predictors for other modelling methods
title: spatialRF: Easy Spatial Regression with Random Forest
text: might love Random Forest, spatialRF loves , , gives tools generate spatial predictors models anyway. first step requires generating Moran’s Eigenvector Maps (MEMs) distance matrix. two options, computing MEMs single neighborhood distance mem(), computing MEMs several neighborhood distances mem_multithreshold(). either case result data frame Moran’s Eigenvector Maps (“just” positive eigenvectors double-centered distance matrix). MEMs made equal, need rank Moran’s . function rank_spatial_predictors() help . output rank_spatial_predictors() list three slots: “method”, character string name ranking method; “criteria”, ordered data frame criteria used rank spatial predictors; “ranking”, character vector names spatial predictors order ranking (just first column “criteria” data frame). can use “ranking” object reorder mems data frame. , spatial predictors can included model one one, order ranking, spatial autocorrelation residuals becomes neutral, possible. little example linear model follows.  According Moran’s test, model residuals show spatial autocorrelation. Let’s introduce MEMs one one problem solved.  Now can compare model without spatial predictors m model spatial predictors m.. According model comparison, can concluded addition spatial predictors, spite increase complexity, improved model. case, just simple demonstration spatial predictors generated functions spatialRF package can still help fit spatial models modeling methods.
code: #single distance (0km by default) mems <- spatialRF::mem(distance.matrix = distance_matrix)  #several distances mems <- spatialRF::mem_multithreshold(   distance.matrix = distance.matrix,   distance.thresholds = distance.thresholds ) kableExtra::kbl(   head(mems[, 1:4], n = 10),   format = "html" ) %>%   kableExtra::kable_paper("hover", full_width = F) mem.rank <- spatialRF::rank_spatial_predictors(   distance.matrix = distance_matrix,   spatial.predictors.df = mems,   ranking.method = "moran" ) mems <- mems[, mem.rank$ranking]  #also: #mems <- mem.rank$spatial.predictors.df #model definition predictors <- c(   "climate_aridity_index_average ",   "climate_bio1_average",   "bias_species_per_record",   "human_population_density",   "topography_elevation_average",   "fragmentation_division" ) model.formula <- as.formula(   paste(     dependent.variable.name,     " ~ ",     paste(       predictors,       collapse = " + "     )   ) )  #scaling the data model.data <- scale(plant_richness_df) %>%    as.data.frame()  #fitting the model m <- lm(model.formula, data = model.data)  #Moran's I test of the residuals moran.test <- spatialRF::moran(   x = residuals(m),   distance.matrix = distance_matrix,   verbose = FALSE ) moran.test$plot #add mems to the data and applies scale() model.data <- data.frame(   plant_richness_df,   mems ) %>%   scale() %>%   as.data.frame()  #initialize predictors.i predictors.i <- predictors  #iterating through MEMs for(mem.i in colnames(mems)){      #add mem name to model definintion   predictors.i <- c(predictors.i, mem.i)      #generate model formula with the new spatial predictor   model.formula.i <- as.formula(     paste(       dependent.variable.name,       " ~ ",       paste(         predictors.i,         collapse = " + "       )     )   )      #fit model   m.i <- lm(model.formula.i, data = model.data)      #Moran's I test   moran.test.i <- moran(     x = residuals(m.i),     distance.matrix = distance_matrix,     verbose = FALSE   )      #stop if no autocorrelation   if(moran.test.i$test$interpretation == "No spatial correlation"){     break   }    }#end of loop  #last moran test moran.test.i$plot comparison.df <- data.frame(   Model = c("Non-spatial", "Spatial"),   Predictors = c(length(predictors), length(predictors.i)),   R_squared = round(c(summary(m)$r.squared, summary(m.i)$r.squared), 2),   AIC = round(c(AIC(m), AIC(m.i)), 0),   BIC = round(c(BIC(m), BIC(m.i)), 0),   `Moran I` = round(c(moran.test$test$moran.i, moran.test.i$test$moran.i), 2) )  kableExtra::kbl(   comparison.df,   format = "html" ) %>%   kableExtra::kable_paper("hover", full_width = F)

what: Multicollinearity reduction via Variance Inflation Factor — auto_vif
title: Multicollinearity reduction via Variance Inflation Factor — auto_vif
text: Selects predictors linear combinations predictors using computing variance inflation factors (VIF). Allows user define order preference selection predictors. Warning: variables preference.order colnames(x), non-numeric columns removed silently x preference.order. happens rows NA values (na.omit() applied). function issues warning zero-variance columns found.

title: Multicollinearity reduction via Variance Inflation Factor — auto_vif
code: auto_vif(   x = NULL,   preference.order = NULL,   vif.threshold = 5,   verbose = TRUE )

title: Multicollinearity reduction via Variance Inflation Factor — auto_vif
text: x data frame predictors result auto_cor(). Default: NULL. preference.order character vector columns names x ordered user preference, Default: NULL. vif.threshold Numeric 2.5 10 defining selection threshold VIF analysis. Higher numbers result relaxed variable selection. Default: 5. verbose Logical. TRUE, describes function operations user. Default:: TRUE

title: Multicollinearity reduction via Variance Inflation Factor — auto_vif
text: List three slots: vif: data frame names selected variables respective VIF scores. selected.variables: character vector names selected variables. selected.variables.df: data frame selected variables.

title: Multicollinearity reduction via Variance Inflation Factor — auto_vif
text: function two modes operation: 1. argument preference.order NULL, function removes iteration variable highest VIF VIF values lower vif.threshold. 2. preference.order provided, variables selected giving priority according order preference.order. variables preference.order, selected option 1. groups variables processed, variables put together selected giving priority ones preference.order. method preserves variables desired user much possible. Can chained together auto_cor() pipes, see examples .

title: Defines a beowulf cluster — beowulf_cluster
text: cluster.ips Character vector IPs machines cluster. first machine considered main node cluster, generally machine R code executed. Default: NULL. cluster.cores Numeric integer vector, number cores machine. Default: NULL. cluster.user Character string, name user (throughout machines), Defaults current system user. cluster.port Character, port used machines cluster communicate. firewall computers must allow traffic port. Default: "11000" outfile direct messages provided workers. working local computer, "" prints worker's messages console. text file path append worker's messages given file.  Default: /dev/null en Linux  nul: windows.

Methods generate spatial predictors: "hengl": named method RFsp presented paper "Random forest generic framework predictive modeling spatial spatio-temporal variables", Hengl et al.
